# Technical Validation: Why This Tutorial Works

This guide provides the official evidence for the best practices shared in the "Scaling Performance" blog post, along with three high-impact scenarios to explain the "Why" to your audience.

## 1. Documentation References

To verify the correctness of this tutorial, you can cross-reference these official Google Cloud and research sources:

### A. Hardware-Aligned Batching (Multiples of 128)
*   **Source**: [Google Cloud TPU Performance Guide](https://cloud.google.com/tpu/docs/performance-guide#batch-size)
*   **Evidence**: "To maximize computational efficiency and minimize padding, the TPU runtime generally requires that your total batch size is a multiple of 64 (8 per TPU core), or a multiple of 1024 (128 per TPU core)."
*   **Why**: TPU matrix units (MXUs) are hardware-optimized for these dimensions. Anything else results in "hidden padding" where you pay for compute cycles that process zeros.

### B. The Linear Scaling Rule
*   **Source**: [Accurate, Large Minibatch SGD: Training ImageNet in 1 Hour](https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.02677) (Foundational paper cited in Google AI blogs).
*   **Evidence**: "Linear Scaling Rule: When the minibatch size is multiplied by k, multiply the learning rate by k."
*   **Implementation**: Google's `tf.distribute.TPUStrategy` and `jax.pmap` are designed specifically to support this data-parallel scaling.

### C. Learning Rate Warmup
*   **Source**: [Google Cloud Training on TPUs: Best Practices](https://cloud.google.com/tpu/docs/training-best-practices#learning_rate)
*   **Evidence**: "For large-batch training, always use a learning rate warmup... This prevents the model from diverging in the early, high-variance phase of training."

